flowRoot.flowPara: Clarify the purpose of working together (use Nine Whys if needed)
Evaluate the standard approach you would normally use for this session
Reexamine and strengthen the purpose statement if needed
Reexamine and decide who needs to participate or be involved
Brainstorm microstructures that could achieve the purpose
Determine the questions and process you will use to evaluate your design
Define step-by-step elements for bringing initiatives or meetings to productive endpoints
Invite a design team (a representative subset of the group) to create a detailed plan, including visual cues, for how participants will interact to achieve their purpose
1-2-All or 1-All in rapid cycles for each step
- Open wall with tapestry paper or flip charts
State the purpose of the initiative being discussed and the DAD and invite brief round-robin introductions

text.tspan: Ask the recorder to recap insights

flowRoot.flowPara: Ask the 7 questions one by one:
1. How do you know the problem is exists?
2. How do you contribute the solution?
3. What prevents you from doing this or taking these actions all the time?
4. Do you know anybody who is able to frequently solve the problem and overcome barriers? What made their success possible?
6. What needs to be done to make it happen? Any volunteers?
7. Who else needs to be involved?
Discover, invent and unleash local solutions to chronic problems
- Facilitator works with a partner to serve as a recorder
- Total group size should be between 5-15 people
- Diversity in roles and experience is an important asset
- DADs take place in a local setting or unit
- Groups may be standing or sitting around a table
- Paper, flip chart or projection equipment is needed to record insights and actions
Working individually, combine the symbols to create the first draft of a story about “the journey” of working on a challenge or an innovation
Create a second draft. Refine the story by dramatizing the size, placement and color of the symbols
Invite another individual or the small group to interpret your drawings. The person who has done the drawing does not speak
Ask the whole group: “Together, what do the drawings reveal?”
Reveal insights and paths forward through non-verbal expression
Invite participants to tell a story about a challenge they face or a common challenge, using only five symbols and no words
Start alone, then in groups of 1-4 people, then the whole group
- Open wall with tapestry paper or flip charts
Introduce the idea of the Ecocycle
Place activities on the Ecocycle, 2-4-All with Post-its on the big wall map
Decide for activities with consensus which to stop and which to start
Create first-action steps for items in the Rigidity and the Poverty trap
Ask all the groups to focus on all the activities for which there is no consensus. When possible, create first-action steps to handle each one
Analyze the full portfolio of activities & relationships to identify obstacles & opportunities for progress
View, organize, and prioritize current activities using four developmental phases: birth, maturity, creative destruction and renewal. Formulate action steps linked to each phase
- Chairs in groups of 4, with or without tables
- Blank Ecocycle map worksheet for each participant & large version posted on the wall
